008/**
009 * Provides access to a precalculated, tiling plane of 2D blue noise, that is, noise without high-frequency components,
010 * as well as seeded modifications to that tiling blue noise plane that make it have even fewer patterns.
011 * Not actually a noise class like {@link FastNoise}. The blue-noise distribution has the practical effect that a value
012 * only appears next to a similar value very rarely. For a quick introduction, see
013 * <a href="https://blog.demofox.org/2018/01/30/what-the-heck-is-blue-noise/">Alan Wolfe's blog</a>, which has many more
014 * useful posts and links that often relate to blue noise and its relatives, like low-discrepancy sequences (which
015 * SquidLib calls quasi-random sequences, like {@link VanDerCorputQRNG}).
016 * <br>
017 * This uses 64x64 grayscale textures 0 through 63 from <a href="http://momentsingraphics.de/BlueNoise.html">Christoph
018 * Peters' invaluable blue noise resource</a>. It may use more of the textures from that site in the future.
019 * <br>
020 * Created by Tommy Ettinger on 10/15/2019.
021 */
022public class BlueNoise {
023    private BlueNoise() {
024    }
025
026    /**
027     * Raw data this class uses, as 64 1D byte arrays. Any of the 1D arrays this holds can be passed to
028     * {@link #get(int, int, byte[])} or {@link #getSeededScratchy(int, int, int, byte[])} as their noiseData parameter. This
029     * group of byte arrays is static, which is probably OK even on Android as long as no one writes to it, and uses
030     * {@link StandardCharsets} to decode itself from a String, which only works on GWT 2.8.2 and newer.
031     * Each byte array can be considered [x][y] indexed or [y][x] indexed; the original images were [y][x] indexed.
032     */

204    /**
205     * The raw data this class uses, as a 1D byte array. You probably don't want to use this field, but you might, so it
206     * is public... but don't write to it. It's static, which is probably OK even on Android as long as no one changes
207     * it, and uses {@link StandardCharsets} to decode itself from a String, which only works on GWT 2.8.2 and newer.
208     * This can be considered [x][y] indexed or [y][x] indexed; the original image was [y][x] indexed.
209     */
210    public static final byte[] RAW_NOISE = ALT_NOISE[0];
211
212    /**
213     * Stores the same values as {@link #RAW_NOISE} if considered [x][y] indexed; available for convenient usage by
214     * GreasedRegion and other classes that can use 2D byte arrays.
215     */
216    public static final byte[][] RAW_2D = new byte[64][64];
217
218    /**
219     * A 256-element array of {@link GreasedRegion}s, each 64x64, where the first GreasedRegion has an impossibly strict
220     * threshold on what points to include (it is empty), but the second has some points far apart, the third has more,
221     * and so on until the last element includes almost all points.
222     */
223    public static final GreasedRegion[] LEVELS = new GreasedRegion[256];
224
225    static {
226        for (int x = 0; x < 64; x++) {
227            System.arraycopy(RAW_NOISE, x << 6, RAW_2D[x], 0, 64);
228        }
229        LEVELS[0] = new GreasedRegion(64, 64);
230        for (int i = -127; i < 128; i++) {
231            LEVELS[i + 128] = new GreasedRegion(RAW_2D, -128, i);
232        }
233    }

235    /**
236     * Gets a byte from the raw data this stores, treating it as an infinite 2D plane of tiling 64x64 regions. You can
237     * interpret the blue noise in many ways, but it is meant to be used with a threshold to select mostly widely-spaced
238     * points when the threshold requires values greater than 100 or less than -100, or irregularly-shaped patterns of
239     * points when the threshold is in the middle, like for values less than 0.
240     *
241     * @param x x position, can be any int; results will repeat every 64 cells
242     * @param y y position, can be any int; results will repeat every 64 cells
243     * @return a byte that obeys a blue-noise distribution, so a value is only next to a similar value very rarely
244     */
245    public static byte get(final int x, final int y) {
246        return RAW_NOISE[(y << 6 & 0xFC0) | (x & 0x3F)];
247    }

249    /**
250     * Gets a byte from some raw data at least 4096 bytes in length, treating it as an infinite 2D plane
251     * of tiling 64x64 regions. You probably want to get the noiseData from an element of {@link #ALT_NOISE}.
252     *
253     * @param x         x position, can be any int; results will repeat every 64 cells
254     * @param y         y position, can be any int; results will repeat every 64 cells
255     * @param noiseData a byte array with minimum length 4096; probably from {@link #ALT_NOISE}
256     * @return a byte that obeys a blue-noise distribution, so a value is only next to a similar value very rarely
257     */
258    public static byte get(final int x, final int y, final byte[] noiseData) {
259        return noiseData[(y << 6 & 0xFC0) | (x & 0x3F)];
260    }

262    /**
263     * Gets a modified byte from the raw data this stores, using seed to adjust repeated sections of blue noise so
264     * patterns are much less noticeable. Unlike {@link #get(int, int)}, this won't repeat every 64 cells on x or y, but
265     * it isn't as correct at matching blue-noise frequencies, and tends to look "scratchy" in places, like TV static.
266     *
267     * @param x    x position, can be any int; results will not repeat for a very long time
268     * @param y    y position, can be any int; results will not repeat for a very long time
269     * @param seed seed value, can be any int; should be the same for all calls that should be from the same 2D plane
270     * @return a byte that obeys an almost-blue-noise distribution, so a value is only next to a similar value rarely
271     */
272    public static byte getSeededScratchy(final int x, final int y, int seed) {
273        seed ^= (x >>> 5) * 0x1827F5 ^ (y >>> 5) * 0x123C21;
274        return (byte) (RAW_NOISE[(y << 6 & 0xFC0) | (x & 0x3F)] ^
275                ((seed ^ (seed << 19 | seed >>> 13) ^ (seed << 5 | seed >>> 27) ^ 0xD1B54A35) * 0x125493 >>> 26)
276                ^ (x + x + y >> 2 & 0x3F) ^ (x - y - y >> 2 & 0x3F));
277    }

340    /**
341     * Generates a 2D int array (as with {@code new int[width][height]}) and fills it with the (seeded variant) blue
342     * noise of this class, finding any points with values less than {@code spillerLimit} when brought into a 0-255
343     * range, and then expanding those points pseudo-randomly while keeping the same value for any expanded range as its
344     * original point.
345     * @param width the width of the 2D array to return
346     * @param height the height of the 2D array to return
347     * @param spillerLimit the upper exclusive bound for the values that will be present in toFill when this finishes
348     * @param rng any IRNG to generate random values during expansion, such as {@link RNG} or {@link GWTRNG}
349     * @return a 2D int array containing ints from 0 (inclusive) to {@code spillerLimit} (exclusive)
350     */
351    public static int[][] blueSpill(int width, int height, int spillerLimit, IRNG rng) {
352        return blueSpill(new int[width][height], spillerLimit, rng);
353    }

355    /**
356     * Modifies {@code toFill} in-place by filling it with the (seeded variant) blue noise of this class, finding any
357     * points with values less than {@code spillerLimit} when brought into a 0-255 range, and then expanding those
358     * points pseudo-randomly while keeping the same value for any expanded range as its original point.
359     * @param toFill a 2D int array that will be modified in-place and entirely replaced; its contents don't matter
360     * @param spillerLimit the upper exclusive bound for the values that will be present in toFill when this finishes
361     * @param rng any IRNG to generate random values during expansion, such as {@link RNG} or {@link GWTRNG}
362     * @return {@code toFill}, after modifications
363     */
364    public static int[][] blueSpill(int[][] toFill, int spillerLimit, IRNG rng) {
365        final int width = toFill.length, height = toFill[0].length,
366                xOffset = rng.next(5) + rng.next(5) + 1, yOffset = rng.next(5) + rng.next(5) + 1,
367                seed0 = rng.nextInt(), seed1 = rng.nextInt();//, noiseChoice = rng.next(6);
368//        final byte[] c0 = ALT_NOISE[noiseChoice], c1 = ALT_NOISE[noiseChoice ^ (rng.next(6)|1)];
369        final Direction[] dirs = Direction.CARDINALS;
370        Direction d;
371        int t, rx, ry, ctr;
372        for (int x = 0; x < width; x++) {
373            for (int y = 0; y < height; y++) {
374                toFill[x][y] = (getSeededSeamless(x + xOffset, y, seed0) + getSeededSeamless(x, y + yOffset, seed1) + 256) >> 1;
375            }
376        }
377        int[] ox = new int[width], oy = new int[height];
378        boolean anySuccesses = false;
379        do {
380            ctr = 0;
381            rng.randomOrdering(width, ox);
382            rng.randomOrdering(height, oy);
383            for (int x = 0; x < width; x++) {
384                rx = ox[x];
385                for (int y = 0; y < height; y++) {
386                    ry = oy[y];
387                    if ((t = toFill[rx][ry]) < spillerLimit) {
388                        d = dirs[rng.next(2)];
389                        if (rx + d.deltaX >= 0 && rx + d.deltaX < width && ry + d.deltaY >= 0 && ry + d.deltaY < height &&
390                                toFill[rx + d.deltaX][ry + d.deltaY] >= spillerLimit) {
391                            toFill[rx + d.deltaX][ry + d.deltaY] = t;
392                            ctr++;
393                        }
394                        d = dirs[rng.next(2)];
395                        if (rx + d.deltaX >= 0 && rx + d.deltaX < width && ry + d.deltaY >= 0 && ry + d.deltaY < height &&
396                                toFill[rx + d.deltaX][ry + d.deltaY] >= spillerLimit) {
397                            toFill[rx + d.deltaX][ry + d.deltaY] = t;
398                            ctr++;
399                        }
400                    }
401
402                }
403            }
404            if(!anySuccesses && ctr == 0)
405            {
406                ArrayTools.fill(toFill, 0);
407                return toFill;
408            }
409            else 
410                anySuccesses = true;
411        } while (ctr > 0);
412        do {
413            ctr = 0;
414            rng.randomOrdering(width, ox);
415            rng.randomOrdering(height, oy);
416            for (int x = 0; x < width; x++) {
417                rx = ox[x];
418                for (int y = 0; y < height; y++) {
419                    ry = oy[y];
420                    if ((t = toFill[rx][ry]) < spillerLimit) {
421                        for (int i = 0; i < 4; i++) {
422                            d = dirs[i];
423                            if (rx + d.deltaX >= 0 && rx + d.deltaX < width && ry + d.deltaY >= 0 && ry + d.deltaY < height &&
424                                    toFill[rx + d.deltaX][ry + d.deltaY] >= spillerLimit) {
425                                toFill[rx + d.deltaX][ry + d.deltaY] = t;
426                                ctr++;
427                            }
428                        }
429                    }
430
431                }
432            }
433        } while (ctr > 0);
434        return toFill;
435    }
